column4: The following new lead was qualified by Dave at Software Advice. Please feel free to mention Dave's name when you first contact the prospect. Questions about this lead should be sent through the Customer Support App. Replies to this email will not be received.

column7: Construction - B2B. Industrial construction company that takes on $5M-$100M projects. They self perform some of the work. This is just the industrial division of a larger company. They offer commercial design/build services as well.
2 to 5 users. 3 users to start out. This may roll out to other divisions as well, but for now they're concerned with the industrial division.
This buyer wants a system that will track upcoming projects, track sales meetings, track interactions, tag contacts, and pull reports.
They used to use Act!, but they haven't had it for several years. They use Gmail internally, but many of the people there are synched with Outlook.
Kara was recently brought on to help get the sales efforts organized, and this is one of the big priorities currently.
They want to get something in place within a few months.
Kara was tasked by a senior vice president to find something for the core business development team.

976623,AMPAM Parks Mechanical,2016-05-13 17:07:51.293,2016-06-30 00:00:00.0,004-Proposal Sent/Reference Checks,1,Open,0,0,3143270,AMPAM Parks Mechanical,2016-05-18 00:00:00.0,,0.0000,8920.0000,0.0000,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,Best Case,,,,"

Contact Information
Job title:    Vice President of Business Development
Office:    (310) 279-7180

Segment:    Construction - B2B. This is for a plumbing subcontractor and design/build firm with a large engineering and design team that focuses on multifamily and hospitality projects exclusively in the state of California. They are ranked the 7th largest contractors in the nation for their respected trade.
Size (Annual Revenue):    $101 million to $300 million. Over $100M/year.
Number of Employees:    501 to 1,000 employees. Right at 1K.

Key features needed:    He wants to have a digital rolodex of clients, contractors, and vendors. He wants to have centralized location to track and communication between their clients, contractors, and vendors. The system should help keep their communication and feedback organized and the correspondence up-to-date in realtime.
Currently using:    Spectrum, Excel, folders. Currently using Outlook companywide. He is open to switching to Gmail for his sales team, for the right system.
Reasons for shopping:    He wants to bring in a CRM solution for his sales guys to track communication with clients easier and more efficiently.
Who they've evaluated:    SalesForce, Dynamics, Hitachi Solutions.
Price expectations:    $125/user/month and $1K/license upfront plus setup costs.

Qualified By:    Brandon

column1: On Jul 21, 2015, at 3:11 PM, Leigh Maloney <lmaloney@manningarchitects.com> wrote:
I was doing some research on CRM systems and when researching Cosential came across a few questions:
What are the IT requirements to purchase Cosential for employees?
None. Cosential is a cloud app.
What are the user requirements? Does each employee need a profile or can we share one profile across a department?
You can have one profile for multiple employees, but you will loose a great deal of functionality. We also have a three user minimum.
If we choose to stop using Cosential after a given amount of time, do we lose our data, or can we have it backed up?
We will send your data back as a MS SQL 2008 database via FTP. You can also export your data using the reporting engine  to Excel.

","6/09/15  -  tt Bill - they are likely sticking w/ Ajera, like the new Purchasing module. Holding off on CRM for now until ERP locked down.  Moving Opp to Nurture - nothing happening here in near term, and unlikely to ever happen if we do not have 2-way integration capability w/ Ajera.
2-way sync is #1 thing for them.  Willing to re-engage on Cosential if and when we can do 2-way w/ Ajera, assuming they keep it.  The Cosential API is probably not the route they want to go... I get the impression they lack the technical expertise and/or bandwidth in-house to take a DIY approach to 2-way sync.

5/29 - NOTE: per Ajera Chat on their website, Ajera API is closed, not open, but they are working on an open version.  (5/29/15)

5/29 - Good demo w/ Bill, Bob, and John - our ability/inability to sync w/ Ajera, 2-way, be be deciding factor. They want to look over API specs.  Bill out next week, we'll talk week of June 8th.  Currently using Ajera on-premise.  Bill and Bob do BD/sales work, John does not, he is most knowledgeable guy about Ajera, not sure what his title is.  Really focused on BD functions - tracking interaction, scheduling tasks/calls, syncing w/ outlook, visibility, reminders, contact list sort.  Almost always sub-contractor, liked Teamed Opportunities in Cosential. Want to sync info from Cosential into Ajera to minimize duplicate entry.  Currently have all project info and pre-project info (when they begin billing time against something) in Ajera, all lead info in a separate Access db that Bill and John use.   Not particularly interested in proposals, we didn't look at it, they do mostly fee proposals. Their Outlook uses Exchange 2013.  Uncertain whether they want to maintain Ajera as acctg/PM software - Ajera is unveiling  a new PO module on the 17th of June, how well that works for them may be deciding factor on whether they stick with Ajera.  2-way integration is their biggest concern - if they do stick with Ajera, then the Ajera CRM module may be most likely solution.  They like Cosential, realize they wouldn't use all features/functions, but could grow into it...  if they can create a push from Cosential to Ajera through our API, that would give us a huge boost.  Sent API info to John.

5/28 - emails w/ Bill - rescheduled demo for 9 am CDT tomorrow.   Bob Fuller and John Mihalic will join us.

4/07- Good intro call w/ Brent - evaluating Cosential on behalf of his engineering client, Mulvaney & Banani of Calgary.  1st demo (Jed & Brent) on 4/09.  Direct Tec is managed services provider for small-mid-sized firms in Alberta, 60-70% of whom are engineering/construction.  Client is Mulvaney & Banani of Calgary (NOT Mulvaney & Banani of Toronto - same name, completely separate company), 50 employees, electrical engineering firm who do a lot of work in oil & gas (?).  Three key things they want above & beyond typical CRM:  1) Ability to manage opportunities w/ multiple roles (they're a member of three different bid teams going after the same project...); 2) streamline proposal process; 3) easily sync emails, documents, drawings to specific project records.  Currently using MS Dynamics SL Accounting (built on SQL Server platform), Outlook (exchange 365; PCs rather than Macs), iPhones, Microsoft/Dell tablets.  Discussed pricing, incl. $5700 implementation w/ FDC - no problem.  Seats TBD, but likely 10-20 full + many (rest of firm?) R-O.  Currently have a custom application for proposals, it has some estimating/calculation components.  Cosential can't do estimating, but they may be able to have Dynamics SL do that and sync it into Cosential, or have their estimating application sync into Cosential through our API.  Will want references eventually.  Time frame TBD:  first demo for Brent, then we'll demo to leadership at Mulvaney & Banani.  Firm has partners, 3 likely to be involved in decision process, one of whom is the CEO (Mick? Nick?) who will be key decision-maker.  Although the firm isn't terribly tech-savvy today, they are investing heavily in tech, sounds like CEO is driving a lot of that.  Sent GoToMeeting for Thursday w/ Brent.  Emailed Brent API documentation.

They may consider making a CRM switch in another 6 months or so.  Moving Opp to Nurture, will check back with Sally later in the year. 

4/09 - sally replied: ""No progress has been made.  I will reach out to you once I hear something and/or we decided to move forward.""  I asked for some clarity on decision-making process & team.  More Emails w/ Sally:  she is only an influencer for CRM side of things, and this is a larger evaluation... which encompasses PM & accounting. No guarantee that CRM will ultimately be a component of the larger software picture.  If it is left out, she may have the ability to pursue alternatives to ACT! on her own, but that's not guaranteed. Her best guess is that the (unnamed) decision-makers will ultimately settle for Deltek Vision (all-encompassing) or possibly invest in a newer, more robust version of ACT!  I reiterated that we can sync w/ Deltek Vision, and can she get me access to decision-makers?

4/08 - emailed again

2/20 - lvm sally again

2/19 - lvm sally

2/06 - demo w/ Sally.  One of her big frustrations with ACT is that she cannot report or look at pipeline by business unit or manager, has to do a lot of exporting and manipulating numbers in a spreadsheet.  Our dashboards make that easy.  She likes Cosential, but still not sure what direction they want to go in for CRM, accounting, etc.  Should have more insight after their meeting on 2/18, follow up with her then.

02/04 - lvm & emailed Sally - my Outlook invite didn't show up for our meeting tomorrow, re-sent.  

1/29 - scheduled demo for 2/05.

1/28 - email exchange, we're trying for 2/05 demo.  Also lvm for sally -she's getting frustrated that Ajera is not getting back to her - I'm not sure what that's about, hoping for more info - i suspect she's looking into their CRM capabilities.  

1/27 - emailed re: reschedule

1/21 - traded emails w/ sally, she needs to reschedule demo again, we're aiming for end of this week.

1/20 - sally has to reschedule, we're trying for 2 pm CST (3 pm EST) tomorrow.

1/16- three offices, maybe 30-40 employees.  Sally handles markeitng end of things.  Likely 4 seats.  Use Ajera, ACT! CRM, hosted.  Word for proposals.  Looking at Cosential vs. Deltek.  Pricing, impleementation reviewed.  Interested in reporting functionality.  Likes that we're building email marketing - they use swiftpage connect for that now (stats don't time back into ACT!).  Scheduled demo for Tuesday, January 20th.

3/14/16 TT Ken. Nothing has changed. Still in process of getting Ajera set up. Didnt sound pleased with how things are going.

4/21 - reconnect w/ Ken, get timing locked in.  Are they finished w/ Ajera?  Ready to move on this?

","

10/1/15 - Still waiting on Ajera implementation.  Call back in December.

7/13 - still waiting on Ajera, per Ken.  Likely september deal.   Frustrating - that's where we were five months ago...  will try to get him on the phone to discuss what the holdup is.  

4/08 - emailed Ken links to 4/22 webinar; I'll check back w/ him later this month.

2/25 - traded emails w/ Ken: "we are in holding patter right now.  Stillinterested, but a bit focused on getting Ajera running correctly on thefinancial and project management side of things.  We were very impressedwith the Cosential product and plan on revisiting this side of things in a fewmonths.".  Please touch base with him in late April.

2/20 - lvm & emailed Ken

2/04 - lvm Ken again

1/21 - Good Demo with Ken, Dianne, and Melissa.  Dianne: Biz Dev Admin, puts together mktg materials and proposals, mostly in Word.  others in office use InDesign.  Melissa, in the NYC office, does BD stuff.  They use Onvia for some leads, but we probably wouldn't set up the integration - they look at a high volume of stuff, only a handful each week are worthwhile.  Discussed pricing & implementation.  They want time to talk over internally, Jed to connect w/ Ken end of next week.  Emailed webinar registration - they might be interested in taking a look at today's proposal webinar (we moved through that pretty quickly at end of demo).

1/15 - lvm for Ken again, he called back and we had exploratory call:   45-person A/E firm w/ offices in Hartford, CT and NYC. Environmental & Transportation, Cultural & Environmental.  Lots of responses to gov't RFPs. Migrating to cloud version of Ajera now, almost complete. Currently using Access for project database, Indesign for proposals.  Lots of SF330s and 255s. 75% sub, 25% prime. Interested primarily in proposal automation. As we talked, some of pipeline mgmt stuff could benefit them as well:  weekly marketing reports (pursuit status), opportunity analytics, ability to tell (when they're a member of multiple bid teams going after same project) which pieces of info/resumes have been submitted to which primes. Ken is VP, wears multiple hats - IT, projects, marketing. Early in process - Ken needs to see it first, then he'll have to get a few others involved to sign off on spend, sounds like there is not a formal budgeting/approval process in place.  Reviewed pricing (approx. $4200 implementation w/ Ajera).  Streamlining collaboration/visibility between the 2 offices important.  Lots of growth in last year or two (by 20-ish people, opened NYC office), have more diverse people/projects. Lack of ability to store detailed project descriptions in Ajera is frustrating them.  Does not want a contact management solution - this is proposals (resumes, cut sheets, gov't forms) + pipeline.  Tentatively scheduled demo for 9 am CST on Wednesday, 1/21, he will check with his marketing folks (whom he'd like to include on demo) and email me to confirm.   ---   1/14 - lvm & emailed

2/19 - sent email and LVM for Dan - ready to discuss where we stand relative to other vendors and tackle next steps?

1/19 - good demo w/ Dan and leadership team - Attendees:  Dan Elkins (IT), Don Jacobs (chairman), Taj (CEO), {another name & role I didn't catch, bad audio}, Tom (something manager), Eric (president), and Tatiana (principal).  Current processes are manual, they update spreadsheet, print, review at Monday morning meeting.  No huge driver on this other than recognizing that they aren't very efficient and sometimes things slip through the cracks.  Demo went very well.  Potential pitfall down the road: we don't integrate with google email, which they use instead of contacts.  Not a problem today, thought.  Use Wind2 for accounting.  Dan said they are scheduled to take a look at one other CRM system (Salesforce, I believe)- that demo may not be happening until next week - and will want some time to discuss/compare the two.  Stay in touch with Dan, he'll remain primary contact.  

1/12- talked w/ Dan, scheduled demo for Monday with partners and some staff (6-7 people).  Do-er / seller model, use Deltek Win2 accounting.  Use google apps for email and calendar, with which we do not integrate.  No firm timeline, no firm budget, but partners will move relatively quickly (allegedly) for right solution.  Also looking at salesforce.  Some proposal work.  Mostly want contact management.

column4: Construction - B2B. They are a design and build firm. They cater to freight construction, building and development, electrical contracting, and fabrication. They provide services to the public and private sectors. All of their work is commercial.
51 to 100 employees. They have around 100 paid employees. She said the total staff is much higher, but they are subcontractors.
11 to 20 users. She said this range is appropriate. She said it could be much higher depending on how many people in each location can use it, but around 13 users will be the minimum.
They need to keep track of current and past customers. They need pipeline management. They need full featured interaction tracking.
She said they need to improve customer relations. They are comprised of 4 separate companies, and they need a way to centralize communications.
She has done some online research on LeadMaster and Salesforce.com.
They want to get something within the next 6 months.
The best time for a scheduling call is usually in the morning EST. She did request some time to coordinate calendars with the rest of the team for demos.

She was tasked by the Director of IT to research CRM systems. She will be reviewing the systems with others on her team, then they will make a collective recommendation. She is expecting scheduling calls, an email, and to do some demos.

10/13 - talked w/ Olwyn - she is marketing consultant, has been with firm since May/June.  16/17 people (including 5 owners, who handle the vast bulk of BD work), a couple of people who do some proposals.  Olwyn uses InDesign, but the other folks (who seem to have the most volume) use Word/Publisher.  Proposal automation important.  She is familiar with Cosential from previous company (I think), firm has nothing in place right now, will either get Cosential or build a bare-bones Access database.  Quickbooks for accounting.  Talked pricing, quoted $2500-$3100 on implemenation (she claims they will have NO data migration).  COO will join us on demo, he will make recommendation to CEO.  (COO is going to take over top spot when CEO retires at end of 2015).  Coordinating via email on demo times next week.

1/26 - stick w/ Chris, he should have budget clarity if board has met.  

","2/09 - email from Chris - budget was not approved - ""they've pretty much shut me down, at least for this year"".  Removing close date from Opp.  Chris would still like to get Cosential, but does not have the budget in 2015.  

1/23 - emailed - update?

1/21 - Got chris's vm again, no msg, will keep calling 

1/14 - talked with Chris Wilton this afternoon:  Board is meeting to finalize budget on Monday.  it should have been wrapped up in December, but they've dragged their feet on budget - apparently they're waiting for clarity on some projects/payments.  It's frustrating to Chris.  There's risk here - we're in Chris's budget, and he wants this done, but if the overall company finances result in reduced budget for his department, then there may not be enough for Cosential.  Board is meeting on Monday, I will talk with him after that meeting.  If his budget is approved on Monday, we'll get this done in January.  

11/13 - sarah intro'd me to chris wilton, he requested pricing proposal.  I suggested we connect this afternoon to iron out seat licenses, then I can generate proposal.  TT Chris - only 3-seat minimum to start with (he doesn't see five firm principals, who do the BD, using this, at least initially).  Really more for Marketing.  Talked through implementaiton & training.  Sending agreement for 3 seats plus Ajera FDC ($6270).   He was not able to confirm when they will sign, although his understanding is that they'd like to get implementation started in 2014.  We may be able to get it signed this week, or someone in finance may decide that they're better off not paying us until 2015 - he and Sarah will figure that out.  Sarah to be OFA, at least initially.

11/11 - sarah's meeting yesterday went well.  she will intro me to a colleague who will run things from here.

10/02 - Demo w/ Sarah -  She liked what we do, wanted to know a lot about Knowledge module.  She is looking at a variety of technology solutions, from CRM to digital asset mgmt.  She'll make recommendation to principals (5 of them, do things by consensus) in next meeting one month from now, next step would be demo for them if we're leading choice.  Business Manager and marketing person already like Cosential.  Use Ajera 8, approx. $4200 for implementation.  55 in-office employees, 3 Marketing people one business manager (BD).  Decision & Purchase by EOY.  Check in with Sarah in late October to find out where we stand.

10/01 - had intro call, demo tomorrow.  Biggest challenge:  communicating updated project data to marketing; accessing most recent writings on a topic.  Use Ajera 8, InDesign.  Sarah is new, looking at a variety of technology solutions to address their challenges.

column4: 11/14 - tt Brent, he has still not narrowed down to 3 vendors... probably won't have that done until an internal meeting on Friday of this week - entire process slower than he thought (so many vendors, so many disparate feature/functions).  Call week of Dec. 1, he should know more then.  Cosential is a leading contender at this point - he knows people in the industry who use us, likes that we're tailored to A/E/C.  Sent CRM implementation ebook and draft of Software Buying Guide to help him in the eval.  Not a 2014 deal.  2015 timing TBD - Brent will be happy if they get it done SOMETIME in calendar 2015.  More insight on timing next month.

10/01 - had exploratory call w/ Brent, scheduled demo for 10/02 at 9:30 am CDT.  Likely January rollout, 6-10 users.  Ajera, $4200-ish for implementation.

The following new lead was qualified by Josh at Software Advice. Please feel free to mention Josh's name when you first contact the prospect. Questions about this lead should be sent through the Customer Support App. Replies to this email will not be received.

column7: Engineering - B2B. They are an architecture and engineering firm. They buyer said they are "big A little e.".
They would like to document contact interactions and schedule tasks. They need detailed notating capabilities to centralize communications. They want to track and generate proposals.
Not Determined. They are open to both web-based and on-premise solutions. He said security is critical.
They are currently using GroupWise for email. He said all of the staff have their own manual methods in Excel.
They don't have a holistic approach to managing clients, and they need to centralize communications.
Screened for up to $1200/user upfront plus 20% annual maintenance or $130/user/month.
They would like to get something by the end of the year.
The best time for a scheduling call is after 9am EST.
He is in charge of research and will be making a collective decision. He is expecting scheduling calls, an email, and to do demos.

9/03 - emailed.  Ley replied that they are not going to invest in CRM at the moment, but will let me know if that changes in the future.

8/20 - Demo:  he liked what he saw, needs to take some time to think it over.  Talked a fair bit about our lack of integration with BillQuick & Quickbooks, what he could do to work around that.  Initially, we can populate Cosential via data migration, but ongoing updates is a concern - project/finance info would require manual update or periodic batch upload to keep both systems in sync.  He isn't sure how easy it will be to drive adoption, since CRM is new to them, but he'll face that with any change/any new system - key is finding the right system.  Will get back to me to discuss next steps (likely demo/discussion with higher-ups)/timeline.  I'll call after Labor Day if I haven't heard from him before then.

8/19 - spoke briefly with Ley (pr: ""Lee""), not a great time to talk right now, scheduled intro call for 1:45 pm today. Talked w/ Lee - wants Quickbooks integration, which we can't do.  Bigger concern is actually migrating data from Quickbooks, which we can do.  After that, someone would need to keep two systems up-to-date manually.  Provided pricing, ballpark $5200 first year.  Lee, President, and VP will make decision.  Pres. & VP will not be on demo, but both appreciate the need for this.  If Lee says ""go"", they will have to okay the spend.  Mostly wants contact database.  Proposal automation also appealing.  Demo tomorrow at 8:30 am CDT.  firm has 3 offices, 25 employees.  Lee is entire BD department.  Not sure on # of seats... could be 3, could be 13.  No specific budget.  He is new to CRM - no idea what to expect in terms of price.  Knows he wants ""project centric"", but isn't even sure what else is out there.  I gave him some basics on the shape of the CRM world, but I think he'll encounter that Quickbooks problem with other project-based CRM systems.

","1/16 - emailed to Paula - they went into holding pattern in late 2014, trying to get this re-engaged this quarter.

8/14 - connected w/ Jim, we're demo-ing (or doing focused, workflow-specific walkthrough) at 9 am EDT on Tuesday, 9/02.  He is going to email me in the meantime w/ some thoughts on what areas he would most like to focus on.

8/06 - Paula emailed me and Jim Johnson (Development Director), asked me to coordinate with him, she is on vacation starting friday, 8/08.  

7/28 - tt Paula - they're a bit gun shy from a failed Salesforce implementation a few years ago (before Paula started).  Want to kick tires on demo instance, salesforce will let them do that.  Talked through that with Paula - what aren't they comfortable with and how can I get them comfortable?  TWO big areas:  proposals (that's Paula - I can show her that), and Salespeople Workflow/usability.  What do salespeople have to do to get information into and out of the system?  That seems to me to be an ""unfamiliarity"" issue - and I don't see it getting solved by giving someone a username and password to a demo instance populated with demo data on a non-tailored configuration... we'll solve that by investing the time to show people how it works.  She is going to talk w/ folks internally and hopefully we can schedule some additional demo time next week, preferably by role (proposals, admin for Paula;  sales/bd functions for the sales/bd guys) - she'll email me.

7/25 - Traded emails w/ Paula:  I'm trying to avoid firm's insistence on access to demonstration account; Paula understands challenges that poses to us, will talk with her Monday (she left office mid-day today).

7/23 - Good demo with Paula and Jim Johnson (biz dev, heads up Grand Rapids office, has been with the firm for about a month).  They were impressed.  Need a couple of days to digest, Jed to connect w/ Paula early next week to talk next steps. 

7/22- emailed w/ Paula, scheduled 1 pm CDT demo for tomorrow.

7/17 - Talked with Paula.  90 employees, 10 w/ BD/marketing responsibilities.  Using Ajera, Nuforma, NO CRM (odd spreadsheets & outlook reminders here and there).  Need centralized platform to track sales & marketing efforts.  No specific timeline, no specific budget - they want to find the right fit.  Paula is Communications Director.  CRM will be ""group decision"", but she did not divulge specifics on who is involved, only that someone in a leadership/finance role asked her to look into Cosential.  Key piece of marketing tracking - Who wants us to call them tomorrow, who wants us to call back in 4 months, how can we manage contact/targeted outreach/etc.  Coming in fresh - no CRM or Cosential knowledge.  Pricing overview, including $4200 ballpark quote for implementation, no objections.  Mostly prime, do a lot of proposals.  I encouraged Paula to include other people (evaluators, decision-makers) in process ASAP to make sure we are addressing everyone's needs.  Next up:  demo, she will wrangle several people on her end.  Emailed my contact info and proposed a few dates, she'll let me know which works best for them.

column4: Construction - B2B. Commercial construction company that does design/build work.

Basic contact management is the primary need for this buyer. Tracking interactions and follow-ups to track outgoing bids is mostly what they need the system to do, so sales reporting and pipeline analysis won't be a big deal. Something that's easy to use with nice features will be what gains the most traction.
They're keeping track of a lot of bids and need a better system in place to do so.
If they found the right system, they would make a purchase quickly.
PLEASE NOTE: The best way to reach this buyer is through email. If you call, call in the morning. He prefers to be reached by email first.
There is a committee that will make the final decision, but Sina (pronounced Seena) is in charge of the first step in the research process.

,"

8/14 - several tries to reach Lisa re: reschedule for this week, haven't gotten a response, so I removed the close date.  

7/29 - traded emails w/ Lisa, conflict on their end (principal had to leave town), we're rescheduling for week of 8/11.  

7/25 - scheduled 5 pm CDT demo on tuesday, 7/29 

7/24 - traded emails:  Lisa reports that Andrew wants another demo/call, trying to lock that in for afternoon of 7/29

7/22 - Paul L. has gone radio silent on me, called Andrew directly and talked w/ Lisa - pitched enterprise @$6k.  She is running it by Andrew, will let me know if that makes sense.

7/11 - Unable to get conf call scheduled w/ Andrew today, we're trying for early next week

7/10 - Paul thinks that's the only way to get this back on track - Andrew is so committed to getting all 22 people on board, but $14-16k year-over-year expense is beyond his means... Paul thinks he'd be a buyer at $6k.  We're trying to set up a call for tomorrow morning.  

Update:  Ajera unable to streamline their workflow at this point, so we aren't going to lose this to ""Ajera does what we want already"".  Apparently connection speed (?) or something has been slow, Andrew may be a bit frustrated with it.  Probably Enterprise or nothing for these guys, should find out tomorrow how realistic it is at $6k.6/23 - good demo with Andrew Murray and Lisa, office manager.  My expectations - what features/functions were initially identified as important to them - were turned around when we actually got on the demo... proposal automation not a key for them.  Better BD, metrics, ease of use, tracking calls, and process efficiency are key.  Their current BD process is managed through Outlook Tasks - not a good fit for what they're doing.  They've cobbled together a tortured workflow that is getting the job done, but it lacks flexibility and transparency... not what Outlook was designed to do.   Andrew likes a lot of what Cosential can do, but he balked at price... not at implementation (I said minimum $4k, maybe more - he has no problem there), but at license cost.  According to him, all 22 people in the firm are do-er/sellers, and ALL would need full-access licenses for this to work the way they want for BD - that's just too much money.  R-O licenses wouldn't work.   I'll see what I can do and get back to him.  In the meantime, he and Paul are going to talk through what under-utilized features of Ajera could benefit them.  Connect w/ Paul in a couple of days to see how that convo went and find out if we can offer Andrew CRM-only licenses $360/user/year (didn't mention that to him).

6/04 - Intro call w/ Danyelle McAllister, Andy Hahn

Andy has 6 mos. asBD Director at Keystone, spent 7 years at an engineering firm prior tothat.  Used Deltek, looked into their CRMcomponent.  Familiar w/ Salesforce – theyare testing 4 SFDC licenses now at a small level.  Using it, but they’re “limping along”.  Do NOT have the enterprise edition at themoment, which will require an extra $5-7k of spend, he thinks, to upgrade/increasetheir capacity to that.  SFDC requires alot of customization, it was not built for the AEC industry. 

Prime, oftensub/partnering.  50/50 prime sub, maybe70/30 (or that may be the goal).

Timeframe and budgetare TBD – they want to see what is out there, what might fit, then could make acase.  Same for number of user licenses.  Talked about execs (VP/CEO) maybe only needingread-only licenses.

Company in businesssince 1997, rapid growth last couple of years.

Started trackingthings using Excel, but they “lose the three-dimensional aspect”.

Marketing &Proposals  -  Danyelle.

Biz Dev – 2 fullydedicated, plus 3 VPs and the owner involved to some degree.

Have ExchangeServer.  Using ADP for timecardtracking.  Timberline for pricing, not for projectmanagement.  Not sure they would want FDCintegration…. “crawl, then walk, then run”. Thinks FDC is a nice to have, not a need to have, especially for asmaller firm.

Project data fromyears past is not organized, is sitting on servers, disconnected. 

Work comesfrom:  1) Relationships.  They’re growing, they are targeting verticalmarkets (who are longer-term, repeat, sizeable relationships – more strategic).   2)  Reed Report – “decent tool to poke around”.  3) SOME chasing RFPs from commercial real estate firms, local businesses.

They are aiming for70/30 or 80/20 on strategic relationship business.  They do some hard bid, private-sector work.Want more construction management work with larger entities (more trust).

Market Sector:  Who do we want to know on the client side(organization/company)?  Who are the keydecision-makers (people)?

Andy does not wantto micro-manage tasks, but appreciates the value of that.  He is more interested in what is theirpipeline by client, by market sector, etc. 

“List of HVACContractors”…  “List of Subcontractors bycategory”.

Went into detail onlicenses and implementation fees, even down to the typical hourlyrates/training breakouts, explanation of how we really only have the strictadherence to hours on the training portion. Scheduled 6/10 demo.

6/06 - Scott called back:  40 person firm, 8-9 offices spread across GA, FL, AL.  Use Ajera, cloud deployment.  Outlook, plus an in-house Access database (that nobody uses very much) for contacts. Spreadsheets for pipeline/forecasting.  Once a month, there is one person in the corporate office who conducts a conference call with each office to go through the pipeline and forecast revenues - "...we have an 80% chance of winning this $300k deal...".  Scott has seen Cosential demo/presentation before, he is sold.  The challenge will be getting the firm principals on board.  Cosential won't give them a ton of stuff that they aren't already doing, it will just make it 10 times easier and faster.  Two most important things to Scott:  1. Client data management;  2. Organizing things for marketing (proposals) - no need to dig, dig, dig to identify similar projects.  Talked up sync w/ Ajera, very appealing.  Firm principals will like reporting, visibility, efficiency.  Scott is out for the next week and largely unavailable the following week, but he is going to try to set up a demo with firm principals (check signers) for (hopefully) last week of June or shortly thereafter.  Please ping him at the end of the month if I haven't heard from him yet on demo scheduling.

5/27 - talked w/ Kristi.  SHe is mktg manager/director, heard about Cosential on a LinkedIn discussion group.  Thinks firm is ready to look at CRM, she really likes proposal automation component of Cosential.  Not sure they are big enough for 3-user minimum, may only want two, but that is something we can discuss in more detail later.  Gave pricing overview, not firm #'s.  She has spent most of her marketing budget this year, may not have it for Cosential, may require getting green light from firm owner.  (Tony Cushieri, I suspect).  He will not be willing to talk with me before a demo.  Biz Dev is really just Kristi and Owner, the office manager does a little bit.  Manages pipeline in Excel, they meet to review it every other week or so.  Use Outlook and Billquick for accounting/timecards.  15-person firm.  Scheduled demo for 3:30 pm CDT on Thursday, 5/29.

,"8/21 - Alice thinks Cosential is a great fit.  Owners not convinced they need a CRM - feel they are too busy to implement and use a CRM.  Alice will let me know if they want to revisit in the future.  Moving to Nurture.

7/30 - previous update from Paul L. was that this isn't going to happen, but I'd like to hear it from them - lvm for Alice Stolen (907-770-4311) - are they interested in revisiting this?    

5/14 - Demo with Mike, Jeff, Alice Stolen, and Dennis (IT Manager), possibly a couple of others sitting in.  Mike stressed that they have moved away from SF330/government work (used to be 50% of their business, is now less than 5%), but still focused on saving time on proposal generation. Have discussed getting a central database (CRM) for years, but have never done it.  Demo went well, talked w/ Dennis for an extra 20 minutes after demo to over technology requirements.  Dennis's big concern:  workflow and processes.  They just don't have those in place, and he isn't sure anyone has the bandwidth or energy to devote to hashing out what processes would look like with new technology (e.g., what fields are required to be completed at what opportunity stages?).

7/07 - keep working to get Joe and Mary on the phone - get templates from Mary, talk through her issues w/ Joe

","7/07 - Unable to get Mary to engage so far on the proposal stuff - Joe hasn't been reachable since our conversation a couple of weeks ago.  Removing close date-  continue trying to talk through with Joe (give him my perspective on Mary's issues). 

6/20 -talked with them, but unable to get Joe to sign off - still hesitating due to Deltek acquisition.   He appreciated the insight into how we handled Win2 and SEMA4, but is not certain that he wants to move forward with Cosential.  Wants to resolve his concerns with Axium first - no timeline.  Figuring out accounting platform higher priority for him.  Difficult time getting Mary to talk through proposals with me - her perspective is very rigid, she is really hung up on the lack of MS word export for SF330 - sent some workaround advice (file convert to Word), suggestions (can include anything you want in ""additional information"" - you don't have to paste images direclty onto the page that says ""additional information"")...  asked her to send me some of their templates, she seems unwilling to do it.  Joe needs time to think this over... 

6/10 - Genterra moving more slowly due to Deltek acquisition, talked strategy w/ Paul - need to get in front of them to address concerns head-on, trying to schedule call for this week.

6/03- Genterra is at the end of their fiscal year, no firm decision yet, they have asked Paul to contact them on 6/06 or 6/09.  

5/13 - Paul @ Axium reports that they're likely to move forward with 3 full licenses, possibly more.  Current quote is for a total of $6160.  Joe (DM) is out of office this week, Genterra is having an internal meeting on or before 5/19, and Paul expects signature shortly thereafter - 75% likelihood it closes in May.  

5/09- demo, went very well.  They'd like to sign up, just need to determine if they can manage the cost and time.  Would love to get started right away, have a proposal coming up that they'd like to use portions of Cosential to facilitate, or at least begin defining workflows & populating data as they sift through things to put proposal together.  Use Echange server (outlook), Act CRM, and Ajera.  Firm principal, Joe Kulikowski, has a lot of goals, and Cosential can address all of them, from SF330 streamlining to assigning Tasks to other people (and tracking them) to Mobile to monitoring Marketing budget vs. actual spend/time on proposals.  Also on demo:  Kim Olsen, accounting, and Mary Frembling, Marketing/Admin Asst.  Paul is going to work on a quote for Joe this afternoon.  Sent Paul several tutorial emails for him to share with Mary, who requested them.  Multiple offices. but small headcount overall (30).

650075,"Bialosky, Axium Sale",2014-05-07 13:28:32.02,,009-Nurture,1,Open,0,0,2201228,Bialosky + Partners Architects,2014-05-15 00:00:00.0,,0.0000,7110.0000,6240.0000,,,,,,,60.0000,720.0000,,,8,,8,,,0,,6/15 -periodic value to Ted,"4/08 - left vm for Ted - update?   Moving this Opportunity to Nurture - no engagement for several months.  

4/03 - emailed ted - still on radar?

3/03 - emailed Ted - still on your radar?

1/12 - emailed to Ted, trying to get him re-engaged

9/22 - Ted has been too busy to engage with me, moved out close date to Q4.  

8/22 - talked w/ Ted, he has been swamped w/ deadlines, strategic projects, etc.  Cosential is Ted's preferred choice, but he has not had the time to put the business case together and firm is so busy it is highly unlikely he can get a decision made before end of August.  We will connect after Labor Day if I do not hear back from him next week.  Pushing the opportunity into September.

8/08 - traded emails re: making business case

7/29 - emailed Ted - questions? ready to go?

7/22 - traded emails w/ Ted, he is reviewing w/ team this week -will let me know if they have questions or just decide to pull the trigger.

7/21 - talked w/ Ted Ferringer- they want Cosential, there have been a couple of holdups to getting this done: 1. CRAZY busy (lots of hiring, lots of projects), and 2. haven't figured out seats/licenses.  Could be anywhere from bare minimum rollout (only Ted really NEEDING full-access - data entry would be concentrated with him - and up to 8 people with other licenses/read-only) to 7 full, 3 R-O.  We'll still honor pricing Sean Gotter gave him.  Accounting team underway with Ajera.  Proposed to Ted:  enterprise - could help solve seat dilemma.  He'd like that - it would give him a reason to put this in front of the DM's and get this thing wrapped up.  Please email quote today, that will give him a chance to get meeting in place with decision team this week.  Possibility for July close.  
Talked w/ Sean Gotter - he had only quoted licenses, did not quote implementation fees (although discussed that implementation fees would be there).
Sent Ted a contract for $3000 enterprise licenses, expires end of month.

5/23 - emailed Sean, word from Ted?  Did he have his other evaluation, anything I can do to help?  On track for May close or June close?  response from Sean:  ""They like us, so we are working with them onprice, with hopes of wrapping up the sale next week or the following.""

5/15 - Sean Gotter recruited me for demo with Bialosky.  Ted Farringer, Director of Business Development (and architect).  Firm partners have tasked him with evaluation and selection of CRM.  Looking at ArchiOffice and something else (presto? something like that), had done some due diligence on Salesforce and decided not a good fit.  Firm had not made business devleopment at ""strategic action"" in the past, that is a new focus - almost everyone do-er/seller.  Great demo, very excited about Cosential's potential for them. Is scheduled to take a look at another CRM system next week, likely decision end of this month, possibly early June.  Asked Sean for quote for 8 full-access users, 8 read-only. Use InDesign for proposals, excited about ability to sync with Ajera.

8/15 -  GET Delshaun on the phone- pull trigger, or enterprise?

","

8/14 - Brent reported last week that DelShaun is close to pulling the trigger. Brent emailed today - hasn't been able to reach him - I tried today, no luck.  Will stick with it.
7/29 - DelShaun OOO today, will be back tomorrow - emailed and lvm for Jerry Slater (who was on May demo).
7/28 - unable to reach Delshaun, Brent reports no feedback from Delshaun.
7/24 - Update from DelShaun - late this afternoon, emailed that he is meeting with president before COB tomorrow, will provide update as soon as he has that meeting.
7/22 - no reply from Brent, vm nm for DelShaun
7/17- Brent update:  convo w/ president hasn't happened yet, he is contacting DelShaun today to feel out enterprise.

7/11 - strategy session w/ Brent:  his meeting w/ principal pushed to next week, but he reiterated that the only hurdle to overcome is comfort w/ Deltek acquisition, and he sees no difficulty.  He agrees Enterprise is a good bet for them - they could have up to 20 users, but Delshaun wants to start small, so we can hopefully drive up the dollars w/ Enterprise.  Brent is going to feel it out on a call today, if it looks like a good bet I'll talk with Delshaun and put together a quote.

7/09 - vm Brent Jones - want to discuss w/ him whether DelShaun is candidate for Enterprise...  this firm is planning a small number of seats initially, want to add later, but we may be able to make it a larger deal with enterprise initially, want to get Brent's perspective on this - if proposing that would slow this down, not worth it.

7/08 - final hurdle - firm principal needs to have convo w/ Axium to resolve lingering concerns over Deltek acquisition (likely wants assurances that Ajera product will be continued to be supported).  Brent Jones has that call scheduled for Friday, 7/11.  Delshaun will have authority to sign after that, assuming principal is reassured.

6/09 - they're taking a step back, thanks to Deltek acquisition.  DelShaun concerned about support for Ajera and FDC going forward.  Proposed that we have a call w/ DelShaun to address, talk through from Cosential's end (we'll support same way as SEMA4 and Win2).  Working on scheduling.

5/27 - per Brent, decision in mid-June.  Talked strategy on how to push investment in all licenses (20-ish, final # TBD) rather than just a few initially (land-and-expand, what Delshaun is leaning toward now).  Brent will keep me posted, actual quote will go to Delshaun next week after Brent's scheduled call with him.

5/23 - Meeting w/ Michelle Kurtz, Erin Westergard, and DelShan.  On our end:  me, Matt, Brent, and Ron (Axium).  Focused on accounting, forecasting, and integration with Ajera and Cosential.  They are impressed with Cosential, DelShaun asked Brent to get him a quote early week of 5/27 once he finalized # of users.  Brent was pushing them to upgrade to Ajera 8 in order to get Cosential, Matt encouraged them to get Cosential implementation underway ASAP.  Michelle asked Brent to wait on Ajera 8 - that will be a separate issue, likely to tackle in June (when Michelle can get an Ajera consultant on-site).  Overall, very positive - should get a Cosential agreement in place relatively soon (I'd estimate early June, chance to pull into May).

5/15 - 90 minute demo with Brent Jones (Axium) and multiple Slater Hanifan people:  DelShaun (Marketing Coordinator), Sherry Edelman (Bus. Dev. Liaison; proposals & resumes along with DelShaun), Michelle Kurtz (Director Finance & Administration), Erin Westergard (asst. Controller, has only been at firm a few weeks), and Jerry Slater (principal?).   Very detailed questions on specifics, not terribly sophisticated on CRM - have just started tracking information on spreadsheets.  Got bogged down considerably in the minutia of Cosental-Ajera integration...  Michelle in particular had a very different focus than the other folks on the call - interested in revenue forecasting, processes, permissioning, all related to financials.  May need to reconvene with her for a separate discussion.  Sending registration link for Proposal webinar to Brent to pass along to DelShaun and Sherry (spelling of her name?).  Provided lots of suggestions for processes/workflows - they're trying to figure a lot of that out.
Slater Hanifan's propsed agenda for 5/15 demo, per Brent on 4/30:
“…Representatives from Marketing, Admin, IT, and Accounting attending the webinar.  I envision the agenda to look something like:

column2: • We’d like to particularly point out the following features: The Central Information Platform, Information Tracking, and the Analytics Functions. I have some questions on my own that I may also ask during this webinar.

","5/27 - tt Brady.  He cannot get owner of firm to engage - that guy is adamantly opposed to spending money on CRM system at this point.  Lots of growth for Allbrite (hiring, spending), please check back in 6 months, they may be in a better position to discuss then.  Brady is a huge fan, just cannot convince owner to consider spend.

4/15 - lvm Dave.  Emailed both Dave and Shelton, got this response from Dave on my question about SAP:  ""...it is still a work in progress, but we were encouraged by what we saw."".  Which I interpret as: they want to work w/ what they have for now.  No next step on the calendar, I'll just plan to ping them again later in the year and find out how things are progressing.

They have something internal called ""CONAG"" that does pipeline management.  Talked pricing, ballpark $6-10 for implementation.  They suggest I reach back out to them April 15th, at which point they should have a better handle on internal capabilities.

3/20- Intro call with Dave Aiken and Shelton Lee.  Looking at Cosential for 10-person US-based group within CEMEX.  Key points:  Using SAP CRM and ERP right now, have found that SAP CRM is too ""transactional"", and insufficiently ""strategical"" - little insight into specific relationships, company structures, and info that can help them develop strategies.  Are meeting first week of April with their SAP CRM folks in Houston, they are going to ask them to make changes to CRM.  If they can do that, great - then they aren't shopping for something new.  If not, or if it is too expensive/time-consuming to configure SAP CRM, THEN they will want to shop for an off-the-shelf solution that fits their needs.  Scheduled demo for 3/25.

2/28 Call Notes (JH):  300-400 in-office employees
6 locations (San Antonio, Dallas, Austin, Fort Worth, Houston, Waco)

Vicki Garrett, in Marketing, is the primary contact. She’s based in San Antonio.  She is familiar with Cosential – used it a previous company (Sawglass? Something like that?) a few years ago, wants to implement it at Brandt.  She is the only dedicated marketing person, but there are a few admin ladies up in Dallas who assist.  Their sales team uses a (homegrown?) sales software called “BSOD”.  It lacks the reporting and proposal automation components that Vicki needs for her work.  Initial evaluation is really just for Marketing, she isn’t sure if we can generate interest from the sales side.  She envisions four user licenses initially, possibly a few more if some of the firm’s VPs are impressed with the reporting functionality.
Integration with that would be nice, if we could do it.

Decision requires approval of a few VPs (San Antonio and Dallas).  She wants to include them on a demo along with the admin ladies who help out in marketing.  Key pieces to highlight on a demo:  Ease of Reporting.  Storing Information.  Running Resumes.  Proposal Automation.
Timeline – ASAP (for her, pending approval of VPs), hopefully within a month.  She understands that full implementation will likely take 12 weeks.

Most of their project data – thousands of projects – is on paper, in folders.  She has already had internal discussions about hiring temps to do lots and lots of data entry to get that project info digitized/uploaded to Cosential.  She expects it would take the better part of a year for them to finish that, understands that it is incumbent upon them to get that done – we can’t do it magically.

He wants to track leads, proposals and closed deals. Also interested in systems that may integrate with his clients' proposal tools, but said it wasn't a deal breaker.
Multiple systems. One uses Sage ACT! and another uses Sugar. Mentioned one client uses ComputerEase for accounting.
Sugar is an open system; they have to relearn the system too often and support is not great. His clients also want to be web-based.
$25-$70/user/month. Seemed to be taking an ROI-driven approach to budget.

10/15- periodic value to Gary and Taryn Ritchie, Diversity Compliance Coordinator.

","5/30 - holding off on Cosential CRM evaluation for time being, reluctant to make an investment of this size.  

5/21 - demo with Gary & Taryn.  Went well.  Taryn used Cosential at SpawGlass - liked it.  Gary's end of things is more product-focused (software), but that is often bundled with services.  Overall, they do RFPs, proposals, function in a project-centric environment.  Feedback positive.  Gary is using Zoho for everything - CRM, accounting, etc - not sure how eager they'll be to make the switch and spend the money, but the project info storage was very appealing - I don't think they get that from current systems.  They were planning to attend proposal webinar, we'll talk after they've seen that and had time to discuss internally.

5/20 - confirmed demo time on 5/21.

5/19 - Traded emails with Gary, who talked with his boss about price, and they are open to that spend.  Tentatively scheduled demo for 5/21. 

5/08 - talked w/ Gary, who signed up for the CRM live demo on 5/06.  This firm does diversity complieance management for a lot of General Contractors.  Work closely with several GC's, including some large ones here in Austin.  Likes the potential of Cosential, but thought price would probably put off his principals.  Before scheduling a demo, wanted to talk with his boss to make sure that the spend wouldn't be prohibitive.    

5/19 Email to Gary:

That would be great, Gary Id love to walk you through Cosential.  Ill be out of the office on Friday, but my calendar is wide open on Wednesday.  I typically budget an hour for a Cosential demo.  What time would work for you Wednesday?

Jed

From: gary.shearod@theentermediagroup.com [mailto:gary.shearod@theentermediagroup.com] On Behalf Of Gary Shearod
Sent: Monday, May 19, 2014 1:44PM

To: Jed Hazlett
Subject: Re: Cosential info, SMPS happy hour

Hi Jed,

I wanted to follow up with you. I would like to set some time to view your demo of your system. I spoke with the boss and she would like to see if we can make this work.

Please let me know when you have some availability on Wednesday or Friday of this week. Otherwise, we could look at next week.

Thank you for your time and consideration.

Regards,

Gary

 

On Thu, May 8, 2014 at 9:28 AM, Jed Hazlett <jhazlett@cosential.com> wrote:

Gary,

Nice talking with you this morning, and I hope Ill have an opportunity to walk you through Cosential.   I know the first-year cost approx. $5k for a minimum rollout ($2k-ish for licenses, $3k for implementation) is fairly substantial for a smaller firm, and we have very little wiggle room on a small deployment, unfortunately.  The only area where we might be able to pare that number back would be on the data mapping/migration component of implementation fee, if you have very little info to migrate from Zoho wed be looking at an implementation fee that might be a few hundred dollars lower, though, not thousands lower.

If your firm principals are open to making budget available, provided we make a strong business case that Cosential is the right fit, then Id love to show you what we have to offer just let me know.

Ive included below the details on the SMPS event this afternoon from 5-7 at the AT&T Center at the edge of campus.  Let me know if you plan to attend.

My best,

Jed Hazlett
column36: Come out and join the SMPS Austin Chapter for a unique Central Austin happy hour at Gabriels Caf. This happy hour will start immediately following the SMPS May Workshop to be held earlier that afternoon. Located on the UT-Austin Campus at the AT&T Conference Center, Gabriels Caf is billed as the quintessential classy university caf and lounge. Gabriels offers an abundant selection of beverages, comfortable couches, and a relaxing view of the UT campus from the outdoor patio.
column42: This cash bar happy hour event is open to both attendees and non-attendees of the SMPS workshop.
column48: Bring a friend and/or co-worker and join us for some great networking, relaxed conversation, and tasty drinks with your fellow members of the A/E/C community. Parking is available at the AT&T Conference Center garage or along nearby street parking. Hope to see you there!

,"

11/17 - no response to recent efforts to re-engage Melissa, moving to Nurture.

6/12- lvm and emailed Melissa re: Axium acquisition - we'll support integration with Ajera indefinitely, no worries.

5/28 - Melissa reports that they are in a 'holding pattern' due to recent upgrade of Autodesk and email server... she'll let mek now when things open up and they can re-engage.

5/27 - emailed

5/19 - lvm

5/13 - lvm for Melissa - feedback from group?  Ready to discuss next steps?

5/05 - Demo with Melissa, Jen Davis (mktg.), Brian (IT guru), Mike Riddel (project manager), Jason East (principal), Steve Kurz, and Mindy (works on Access database).  Went well... they had tried to create a project database on their own, but it didn't go well.  Not sure if they'll want Ajera sync on project info (although I can't imagine why they wouldn't).  Talked pricing, quoted $3100-6500 on implementation.  They will want tome time to talk things over.  After demo, emailed Melissa some answers to questions raised on the demo (Onvia vs. FedBizOpps; SF330 video; file types).  

5/1 - talked w/ Melissa.  Using Axium - either ""Ajera Complete"" or ""Ajera Portfolio"" - sounds like on-premise deployment, talked only about one-way sync w/ FDC.  Biz Dev folks track things on their own, usually in Excel.  They have an Access database for tracking contacts.  Melissa is essentially their CRM system - she keeps everything organized and up to date.  Outlook for email and calendars.  They are very interested in proposals.  Moderately experienced software buyers - have a process in place:  the ""IT Task Force"", comprised of a couple of do-er/sellers (PMs, I thinkg), firm partners, and a tech person or two.  Talked price, gave $3100-$6500 as range for implementation.  No firm timeline; maybe summertime, probably this year.  On ""wish list"", but no budget specifically allocated.  Discussed implementation timeline, steps, etc.  Eventually she will want to talk to a local reference (IN, OH, or KY), understands that will be second-to-last step.  Scheduled demo for Monday, 5/05 - members of IT Task Force will participate.

4/29 - traded emails w/ Melissa, tentatively scheduled to chat late tomorrow morning or early afternoon.

4/22 - lvm Melissa

4/10 - emailed again: connect tomorrow?

email exchange through 4/02/14:  

Hi Melissa

Im free between 10 and 2 pm CDT tomorrow.  A Cosential demo is typically an hour, but Im not 100% sure thats the right step for us  if you are primarily interested in the way our software integrates with Axium Ajera, we might be able to tackle that in a quick phone call.  I can talk through the process, what data points can sync between the two systems, etc., but I cant actually show it on a demo I dont have Ajera installed.   I also find that I can run a much better, more focused demo if I have a chance to talk with you first, that way I dont spend our demo time highlighting features & functions that arent important to you.

Im flexible between now and 11:30 CDT, and free again after 3:30 CDT could we tag up for a quick call 15 minutes max and then put a demo on the calendar?

Jed

Jed- How does tomorrow look for you? How long is the demo?
Thanks!

My calendar is still open between 11 and 12 EDT.  Would 11 work for you?

Jed

interview with Tom Neary  Q. When you think about the future of the business development/marketing of professional services - do you foresee any changes in the way the job is done? Or trends for the future?

A: It seems to me that the future keeps showing up at the front door. The pace of change with regard to technology, access to information, and the increasingly global marketplace all contribute to some of the most exciting times ever in our industry, despite the recent years of a down market. The biggest challenge for everyone going forward is similar to what many of us already face today - keeping up with all the information flowing into our respective lives each day, and filtering through it effectively enough to do our jobs well.

Hi Reid:
I had a phone conversation with her for about an hour on Friday which was
great. I have a demo scheduled with her 12/13/10 at 930am, onsite. Their
office is about 20 minutes from my house. I''m also talking to her about
volunteering for SMPS Florida (she is past president and currently on the
board). Also, their firm is looking to hire Carol Doscher (client of ours
and keynote speaker at our User Conference) in January of next year. So,
I''ll take this lead for now and give to you if I can (believe me, I wish I
could hand over to you now!).
Oh heck, I''ll make this the call log. They had demo a few years ago with
Dan and although interested, they didn''t feel like we were quite at the
point that it worked for them.
Demo Note: Dan gave her demo few years back and although she liked
product/Dan she did mention that she got the impression that Dan is very
involved on development side and that it was like having her engineer
husband explain something to her (quickly and with jargon). She noted that
she felt like I understood her pain points.
Web site update: She was impressed with web site update and felt that it
demonstrated our expanded capabilities and did a much better job of quickly
and clearly demonstrating value analysis. She said all I want to know when
I get to site is ""How does this make my life easier?"" and that our current
site did a better job of conveying.
Interested in Ethnos connection especially. They have nothing now. No ideas
what system financial data system they use. Asked that I send her
implementation questionnaire so she could be prepared.
Best,
Christina
